    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-02-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <head>4. National Security Study Memorandum 14<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d4fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–134, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> Files,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 14. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-02-05">February 5, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director for Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. China Policy</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a study be prepared on U.S. Policy Towards China,
                    on U.S. objectives and interests involved and the broad lines of appropriate
                    U.S. policies. The study should incorporate alternative views and
                    interpretations of the issues involved. It should include summary statements of
                    the conceptions and policy lines of the previous administration.</p>
                <p>The Study should include the following: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The current status of U.S. relations with Communist China and the
                            Republic of China;</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The nature of the Chinese Communist threat and intentions in
                            Asia;</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>The interaction between U.S. policy and the policies of other major
                            interested countries toward China;</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Alternative U.S. approaches on China and their costs and risks.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The President has directed that the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    Interdepartmental Group for East Asia perform this study.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d4fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWG1">Winthrop G. Brown</persName>, Acting Chairman of
                        the East Asia and Pacific Interdepartmental Group, oversaw the completion of
                        this study, the first draft of which was submitted to the <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Senior Review Group on April 29 and
                        discussed in a May 15 meeting. See <ref target="#d13">Document 13</ref>. A
                        summary of the <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> response to <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 14 is printed as <ref target="#d12"
                            >Document 12</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The paper should be forwarded to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Review
                    Group by March 10.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
